00:44:45.920 --> 00:44:48.540
So let's talk about
multi-threaded OpenGL.

00:44:48.590 --> 00:44:52.290
So what we've done for Leopard
is an exciting new feature,

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:55.680
where we've realized that a
lot of applications themselves

00:44:55.680 --> 00:44:58.170
tend to be single-threaded,
particularly games.

00:44:58.240 --> 00:45:03.820
And games also tend to run open
at a sort of open-loop frame rate.

00:45:03.820 --> 00:45:06.660
They're driving as hard as they can
to get as many frames as they can.

00:45:06.660 --> 00:45:10.280
So what this means is games are
pushing hard against the OpenGL stack.

00:45:10.320 --> 00:45:14.800
And the OpenGL stack has to do a little
bit of work to actually get commands

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:18.760
ready to go up to the GPU so the
graphics card can actually draw them.

00:45:18.780 --> 00:45:22.220
So in Leopard,
you're going to be able to take and

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:27.860
tell the OpenGL stack that it needs to
farm out some of that task of preparing

00:45:27.860 --> 00:45:31.860
the list of things to do for the
GPU and move that onto a second thread.

00:45:31.920 --> 00:45:35.680
So in a multi-core or a
multi-processor machine,

00:45:35.680 --> 00:45:37.140
you're going to get a net benefit.

00:45:37.190 --> 00:45:40.980
Because let's say, for example,
in this somewhat contrived example-- it's

00:45:40.980 --> 00:45:43.990
a little more complicated than this--
if I have an application that's spending

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:49.180
60% of its time in my game logic,
it's spending 30% of its time

00:45:49.270 --> 00:45:50.980
pushing up against OpenGL,
waiting for the

00:45:51.070 --> 00:45:54.380
OpenGL framework to do things,
and you have another remaining 10%

00:45:54.440 --> 00:45:56.260
of time spent doing other stuff.

00:45:56.260 --> 00:46:00.960
If you turn on multi-threaded OpenGL,
we're able to take maybe 20% to 25%

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:04.180
of the work spent in the OpenGL stack
and farm that on the second thread,

00:46:04.180 --> 00:46:07.550
which suddenly makes your main
thread have about 20% to 25% more

00:46:07.630 --> 00:46:11.820
cycles available for it to push
harder and generate more frame rate.

00:46:12.020 --> 00:46:14.490
Now,
this is an opt-in option for developers,

00:46:14.850 --> 00:46:18.520
because not all OpenGL applications
are suitable to have this enabled,

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:23.680
because the way they use OpenGL may
induce synchronization points,

00:46:23.680 --> 00:46:26.400
where we actually have to either check
with the OpenGL framework or possibly

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:30.140
even through the driver to the card
to determine some current state.

00:46:30.200 --> 00:46:34.180
So things like glget will create
these synchronization points,

00:46:34.180 --> 00:46:37.230
which means that we cannot get
the parallelism we need with

00:46:37.260 --> 00:46:39.320
a multi-threaded OpenGL stack.

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:41.820
So you want to really watch
your state management.

00:46:41.820 --> 00:46:46.140
And to help you do that,
the OpenGL and MacÂ OSÂ X section is

00:46:46.200 --> 00:46:49.240
going to talk about conceptually
the multi-threaded GL stack.

00:46:49.240 --> 00:46:50.980
And also,
it'll be touched a little bit in

00:46:50.980 --> 00:46:53.000
the optimization sessions as well.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:56.050
So let's look at where this
gets us in terms of performance.

00:46:56.060 --> 00:47:01.480
We've taken Doom 3 and World of
Warcraft and done before and afters.

00:47:01.600 --> 00:47:06.120
So you look at, in the case of Doom 3,
when it's off,

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:09.150
we're getting about 109 frames
per second on a Mac Pro.

00:47:09.260 --> 00:47:11.560
When we turn it on,
we hit 160 frames per second.

00:47:11.560 --> 00:47:14.970
And again,
this is just throwing a switch.

00:47:14.980 --> 00:47:20.280
On World of Warcraft, Ironforge,
which is a very crowd-intensive

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:24.280
benchmark-type scene,
we're getting 48 frames

00:47:24.280 --> 00:47:25.190
per second with it off.

00:47:25.240 --> 00:47:28.430
We flip it on, and we're getting around
