00:48:13.540 --> 00:48:15.940
And it's got a couple of interesting
details you want to check out.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:18.340
One is this concept of
automatic or implicit animation,

00:48:18.340 --> 00:48:21.770
where all my application,
my game would need to do is

00:48:21.820 --> 00:48:26.840
put graphic elements on layers,
tell core animation where the layers are,

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:29.530
and then tell core animation what
needs to happen with the layers,

00:48:29.540 --> 00:48:32.050
like the layer needs to go
across the screen and fade out.

00:48:32.080 --> 00:48:34.070
And core animation takes it from there.

00:48:34.080 --> 00:48:37.220
It basically, you know,
on its own rendering thread,

00:48:37.220 --> 00:48:40.480
its own rendering engine,
takes it and animates that scene.

00:48:40.480 --> 00:48:43.800
You're out of the business of
driving each frame of the animation.

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:45.960
And this enables us to
do all sorts of stuff.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:50.040
With making it a really efficient
system where we're able to ensure,

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:53.140
you know, do our best to optimally draw
the scene and ensure that

00:48:53.140 --> 00:48:54.710
we get maximal frame rate.

00:48:54.720 --> 00:48:58.230
And also in simple scenes,
we don't draw too fast and end

00:48:58.300 --> 00:49:01.820
up trying to draw 3,000 frames
per second on a trivial scene,

00:49:01.820 --> 00:49:03.640
even when the user's
only going to see 60.

00:49:03.640 --> 00:49:05.950
So I really think this should
be interesting for you guys

00:49:06.100 --> 00:49:07.450
to check out for casual games.

00:49:09.430 --> 00:49:11.490
